><gtr:grantReference>ES/J006602/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Concerned with ?the return of the sweatshop? as a main way of doing business in garment manufacturing, in his PhD thesis Jeronimo aimed at identifying the changes that the fashion industry has experienced in the transition from Fordism to Neoliberalism, and their consequences over working conditions.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>During his Post Doctoral Fellowship (2012-2013), Jeronimo?s main objectives are: (a) to do some limited follow up research; and (b) to disseminate the findings of his PhD. Regarding the former, Dr Montero will conduct two months of fieldwork in Buenos Aires. The focus will be primarily put on better understanding state regulation/non regulation of informal labour as the broader context within which ?national sweatshops? have expanded to unprecedented levels, in the midst of a strong economic recovery (2002-2010).&lt;/p>

&lt;p>With regards to dissemination, Jeronimo aims to contact media in both locations of his PhD fieldwork (Buenos Aires and Prato, Italy); to participate in a number of academic events; and, most notably, to publish four papers in academic journals. Potential issues for these papers are:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>fashion and ?modern slavery'&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>trade unions and migrant labour in Buenos Aires&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>informal labour in Italian industrial districts&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>informal labour and the state in the Global South.&lt;/li>

